# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jpeg-xl
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A **discrete cosine transform** (**DCT**) expresses a finite sequence of data points in terms of a sum of cosine functions oscillating at different frequencies.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT, first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, is a widely used transformation technique in signal processing and data compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are also important to numerous other applications in science and engineering, such as digital signal processing, telecommunication devices, reducing network bandwidth usage, and spectral methods for the numerical solution of partial differential equations.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT is a Fourier-related transform similar to the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), but using only real numbers.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCTs are generally related to Fourier series coefficients of a periodically and symmetrically extended sequence whereas DFTs are related to Fourier series coefficients of only periodically extended sequences.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are equivalent to DFTs of roughly twice the length, operating on real data with even symmetry (since the Fourier transform of a real and even function is real and even), whereas in some variants the input or output data are shifted by half a sample.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] There are eight standard DCT variants, of which four are common.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The most common variant of discrete cosine transform is the type-II DCT, which is often called simply *the DCT*.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This was the original DCT as first proposed by Ahmed.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Its inverse, the type-III DCT, is correspondingly often called simply *the inverse DCT* or *the IDCT*.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Two related transforms are the discrete sine transform (DST), which is equivalent to a DFT of real and odd functions, and the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which is based on a DCT of overlapping data.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional DCTs (MD DCTs) are developed to extend the concept of DCT to multidimensional signals.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A variety of fast algorithms have been developed to reduce the computational complexity of implementing DCT.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] One of these is the integer DCT (IntDCT), an integer approximation of the standard DCT, used in several ISO/IEC and ITU-T international standards.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT compression, also known as block compression, compresses data in sets of discrete DCT blocks.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT blocks sizes including 8 × 8 pixels for the standard DCT, and varied integer DCT sizes between 4 × 4 and 32 × 32 pixels.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT has a strong *energy compaction* property, capable of achieving high quality at high data compression ratios.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] However, blocky compression artifacts can appear when heavy DCT compression is applied.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT was first conceived by Nasir Ahmed while working at Kansas State University.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The concept was proposed to the National Science Foundation in 1972.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT was originally intended for image compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Ahmed developed a practical DCT algorithm with his PhD students T.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Rao at the University of Texas at Arlington in 1973.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] They presented their results in a January 1974 paper, titled *Discrete Cosine Transform*.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] It described what is now called the type-II DCT (DCT-II), as well as the type-III inverse DCT (IDCT).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Since its introduction in 1974, there has been significant research on the DCT.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In 1977, Wen-Hsiung Chen published a paper with C.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Fralick presenting a fast DCT algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Further developments include a 1978 paper by M.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] These research papers, along with the original 1974 Ahmed paper and the 1977 Chen paper, were cited by the Joint Photographic Experts Group as the basis for JPEG's lossy image compression algorithm in 1992.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The discrete sine transform (DST) was derived from the DCT, by replacing the Neumann condition at *x=0* with a Dirichlet condition.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DST was described in the 1974 DCT paper by Ahmed, Natarajan and Rao.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A type-I DST (DST-I) was later described by Anil K.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Jain in 1976, and a type-II DST (DST-II) was then described by H.B.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Robinson adapted the DCT for inter-frame motion-compensated video coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Jain further developed motion-compensated DCT video compression, also called block motion compensation.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This led to Chen developing a practical video compression algorithm, called motion-compensated DCT or adaptive scene coding, in 1981.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Motion-compensated DCT later became the standard coding technique for video compression from the late 1980s onwards.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT variant, the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), was developed by John P.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Bradley at the University of Surrey in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The MDCT is used in most modern audio compression formats, such as Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3 (which uses a hybrid DCT-FFT algorithm), Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), and Vorbis (Ogg).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Nasir Ahmed also developed a lossless DCT algorithm with Giridhar Mandyam and Neeraj Magotra at the University of New Mexico in 1995.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This allows the DCT technique to be used for lossless compression of images.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] It is a modification of the original DCT algorithm, and incorporates elements of inverse DCT and delta modulation.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] It is a more effective lossless compression algorithm than entropy coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is the most widely used transformation technique in signal processing, and by far the most widely used linear transform in data compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT compression standards are used in digital media technologies, such as digital images, digital photos, digital video, streaming media, digital television, streaming television, video on demand (VOD), digital cinema, high-definition video (HD video), and high-definition television (HDTV).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT, and in particular the DCT-II, is often used in signal and image processing, especially for lossy compression, because it has a strong *energy compaction* property.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In typical applications, most of the signal information tends to be concentrated in a few low-frequency components of the DCT.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For strongly correlated Markov processes, the DCT can approach the compaction efficiency of the Karhunen-Loève transform (which is optimal in the decorrelation sense).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] As explained below, this stems from the boundary conditions implicit in the cosine functions.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are widely employed in solving partial differential equations by spectral methods, where the different variants of the DCT correspond to slightly different even and odd boundary conditions at the two ends of the array.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are closely related to Chebyshev polynomials, and fast DCT algorithms (below) are used in Chebyshev approximation of arbitrary functions by series of Chebyshev polynomials, for example in Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is widely used in many applications, which include the following.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II is an important image compression technique.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] It is used in image compression standards such as JPEG, and video compression standards such as H.26x, MJPEG, MPEG, DV, Theora and Daala.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] There, the two-dimensional DCT-II of $N\times N$ blocks are computed and the results are quantized and entropy coded.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In this case, N is typically 8 and the DCT-II formula is applied to each row and column of the block.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The result is an 8 × 8 transform coefficient array in which the $(0,0)$ element (top-left) is the DC (zero-frequency) component and entries with increasing vertical and horizontal index values represent higher vertical and horizontal spatial frequencies.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The integer DCT, an integer approximation of the DCT, is used in Advanced Video Coding (AVC), introduced in 2003, and High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC), introduced in 2013.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The integer DCT is also used in the High Efficiency Image Format (HEIF), which uses a subset of the HEVC video coding format for coding still images.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] HEVC and HEIF use varied block sizes between 4 x 4 and 32 x 32 pixels.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] As of 2019, AVC is by far the most commonly used format for the recording, compression and distribution of video content, used by 91% of video developers, followed by HEVC which is used by 43% of developers.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional DCTs (MD DCTs) have several applications, mainly 3-D DCTs such as the 3-D DCT-II, which has several new applications like Hyperspectral Imaging coding systems, variable temporal length 3-D DCT coding, video coding algorithms, adaptive video coding and 3-D Compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Due to enhancement in the hardware, software and introduction of several fast algorithms, the necessity of using MD DCTs is rapidly increasing.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT-IV has gained popularity for its applications in fast implementation of real-valued polyphase filtering banks, lapped orthogonal transform and cosine-modulated wavelet bases.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT plays an important role in digital signal processing specifically data compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is widely implemented in digital signal processors (DSP), as well as digital signal processing software.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Many companies have developed DSPs based on DCT technology.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are widely used for applications such as encoding, decoding, video, audio, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, and analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A common issue with DCT compression in digital media are blocky compression artifacts, caused by DCT blocks.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In a DCT algorithm, an image (or frame in an image sequence) is divided into square blocks which are processed independently from each other, then the DCT blocks is taken within each block and the resulting DCT coefficients are quantized.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This process can cause blocking artifacts, primarily at high data compression ratios.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This can also cause the mosquito noise effect, commonly found in digital video.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT blocks are often used in glitch art.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The artist Rosa Menkman makes use of DCT-based compression artifacts in her glitch art, particularly the DCT blocks found in most digital media formats such as JPEG digital images and MP3 audio.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Another example is *Jpegs* by German photographer Thomas Ruff, which uses intentional JPEG artifacts as the basis of the picture's style.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Like any Fourier-related transform, DCTs express a function or a signal in terms of a sum of sinusoids with different frequencies and amplitudes.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Like the DFT, a DCT operates on a function at a finite number of discrete data points.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The obvious distinction between a DCT and a DFT is that the former uses only cosine functions, while the latter uses both cosines and sines (in the form of complex exponentials).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] However, this visible difference is merely a consequence of a deeper distinction: a DCT implies different boundary conditions from the DFT or other related transforms.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The Fourier-related transforms that operate on a function over a finite domain, such as the DFT or DCT or a Fourier series, can be thought of as implicitly defining an *extension* of that function outside the domain.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] That is, once you write a function $f(x)$ as a sum of sinusoids, you can evaluate that sum at any x , even for x where the original $f(x)$ was not specified.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DFT, like the Fourier series, implies a periodic extension of the original function.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT, like a cosine transform, implies an even extension of the original function.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] However, because DCTs operate on *finite*, *discrete* sequences, two issues arise that do not apply for the continuous cosine transform.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] First, one has to specify whether the function is even or odd at *both* the left and right boundaries of the domain (i.e. the min-*n* and max-*n* boundaries in the definitions below, respectively).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Second, one has to specify around *what point* the function is even or odd.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, consider a sequence *abcd* of four equally spaced data points, and say that we specify an even *left* boundary.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] There are two sensible possibilities: either the data are even about the sample *a*, in which case the even extension is *dcbabcd*, or the data are even about the point *halfway* between *a* and the previous point, in which case the even extension is *dcbaabcd* (*a* is repeated).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Each boundary can be either even or odd (2 choices per boundary) and can be symmetric about a data point or the point halfway between two data points (2 choices per boundary), for a total of 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 = 16 possibilities.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] These choices lead to all the standard variations of DCTs and also discrete sine transforms (DSTs).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Half of these possibilities, those where the *left* boundary is even, correspond to the 8 types of DCT; the other half are the 8 types of DST.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] These different boundary conditions strongly affect the applications of the transform and lead to uniquely useful properties for the various DCT types.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Most directly, when using Fourier-related transforms to solve partial differential equations by spectral methods, the boundary conditions are directly specified as a part of the problem being solved.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Or, for the MDCT (based on the type-IV DCT), the boundary conditions are intimately involved in the MDCT's critical property of time-domain aliasing cancellation.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In a more subtle fashion, the boundary conditions are responsible for the *energy compactification* properties that make DCTs useful for image and audio compression, because the boundaries affect the rate of convergence of any Fourier-like series.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, it is well known that any discontinuities in a function reduce the rate of convergence of the Fourier series so that more sinusoids are needed to represent the function with a given accuracy.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The same principle governs the usefulness of the DFT and other transforms for signal compression; the smoother a function is, the fewer terms in its DFT or DCT are required to represent it accurately, and the more it can be compressed.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] However, the implicit periodicity of the DFT means that discontinuities usually occur at the boundaries: any random segment of a signal is unlikely to have the same value at both the left and right boundaries.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In contrast, a DCT where *both* boundaries are even *always* yields a continuous extension at the boundaries (although the slope is generally discontinuous).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This is why DCTs, and in particular DCTs of types I, II, V, and VI (the types that have two even boundaries) generally perform better for signal compression than DFTs and DSTs.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In practice, a type-II DCT is usually preferred for such applications, in part for reasons of computational convenience.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Formally, the discrete cosine transform is a linear, invertible function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{N}\to \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ (where $\mathbb {R}$ denotes the set of real numbers), or equivalently an invertible N × N square matrix.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] There are several variants of the DCT with slightly modified definitions.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-I is exactly equivalent (up to an overall scale factor of 2), to a DFT of $2(N-1)$ real numbers with even symmetry.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a DCT-I of $N=5$ real numbers $a\ b\ c\ d\ e$ is exactly equivalent to a DFT of eight real numbers $a\ b\ c\ d\ e\ d\ c\ b$ (even symmetry), divided by two.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Note, however, that the DCT-I is not defined for N less than 2, while all other DCT types are defined for any positive N .
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, the DCT-I corresponds to the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=0$ and even around $n=N-1$ ; similarly for $X_{k}$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II is probably the most commonly used form, and is often simply referred to as the *DCT*.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This transform is exactly equivalent (up to an overall scale factor of 2) to a DFT of $4N$ real inputs of even symmetry, where the even-indexed elements are zero.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT-II transformation is also possible using $2N$ signal followed by a multiplication by half shift.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Some authors further multiply the $X_{0}$ term by $1/{\sqrt {N\,}}\,$ and multiply the rest of the matrix by an overall scale factor of ${\textstyle {\sqrt {{2}/{N}}}}$ (see below for the corresponding change in DCT-III).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the DCT-II matrix orthogonal, but breaks the direct correspondence with a real-even DFT of half-shifted input.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This is the normalization used by Matlab.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In many applications, such as JPEG, the scaling is arbitrary because scale factors can be combined with a subsequent computational step (e.g. the quantization step in JPEG), and a scaling can be chosen that allows the DCT to be computed with fewer multiplications.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II implies the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=-1/2$ and even around $n=N-1/2\,$ ; $X_{k}$ is even around $k=0$ and odd around $k=N$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Because it is the inverse of DCT-II up to a scale factor (see below), this form is sometimes simply referred to as the inverse DCT (IDCT).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the DCT-III matrix orthogonal, but breaks the direct correspondence with a real-even DFT of half-shifted output.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A variant of the DCT-IV, where data from different transforms are *overlapped*, is called the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-IV implies the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=-1/2$ and odd around $n=N-1/2$ ; similarly for $X_{k}$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs of types I–IV treat both boundaries consistently regarding the point of symmetry: they are even or odd around either a data point for both boundaries or halfway between two data points for both boundaries.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] By contrast, DCTs of types V-VIII imply boundaries that are even or odd around a data point for one boundary and halfway between two data points for the other boundary.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In other words, DCT types I–IV are equivalent to real-even DFTs of even order (regardless of whether N is even or odd), since the corresponding DFT is of length $2(N-1)$ (for DCT-I) or $4N$ (for DCT-II and III) or $8N$ (for DCT-IV).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The four additional types of discrete cosine transform correspond essentially to real-even DFTs of logically odd order, which have factors of $N\pm {1}/{2}$ in the denominators of the cosine arguments.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] However, these variants seem to be rarely used in practice.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] One reason, perhaps, is that FFT algorithms for odd-length DFTs are generally more complicated than FFT algorithms for even-length DFTs (e.g., the simplest radix-2 algorithms are only for even lengths), and this increased intricacy carries over to the DCTs as described below.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Not that the trivial real-even array, a length-one DFT (odd length) of a single number a , corresponds to a DCT-V of length $N=1$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Using the normalization conventions above, the inverse of DCT-I is DCT-I multiplied by 2/(*N* − 1).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of DCT-IV is DCT-IV multiplied by 2/*N*.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of DCT-II is DCT-III multiplied by 2/*N* and vice versa.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Like for the DFT, the normalization factor in front of these transform definitions is merely a convention and differs between treatments.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, some authors multiply the transforms by ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2/N}}}$ so that the inverse does not require any additional multiplicative factor.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Combined with appropriate factors of √2 (see above), this can be used to make the transform matrix orthogonal.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional variants of the various DCT types follow straightforwardly from the one-dimensional definitions: they are simply a separable product (equivalently, a composition) of DCTs along each dimension.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a two-dimensional DCT-II of an image or a matrix is simply the one-dimensional DCT-II, from above, performed along the rows and then along the columns (or vice versa).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of a multi-dimensional DCT is just a separable product of the inverses of the corresponding one-dimensional DCTs (see above), e.g., the one-dimensional inverses applied along one dimension at a time in a row-column algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Technically, computing a two-, three- (or -multi) dimensional DCT by sequences of one-dimensional DCTs along each dimension is known as a *row-column* algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] As with multidimensional FFT algorithms, however, there exist other methods to compute the same thing while performing the computations in a different order (i.e., interleaving or combining the algorithms for the different dimensions).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Owing to the rapid growth in the applications based on the 3-D DCT, several fast algorithms have been developed for the computation of 3-D DCT-II.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Vector-Radix algorithms are applied for computing M-D DCT to reduce the computational complexity and to increase the computational speed.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Vector-Radix Decimation in Frequency (VR DIF) is an example of an algorithm to compute a 3-D DCT-II efficiently.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In order to apply the VR DIF algorithm, the input data must be formulated and rearranged as follows.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The transform size *N × N × N* is assumed to be 2.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The adjacent figure shows the four stages that are involved in calculating 3-D DCT-II using VR DIF algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The first stage is the 3-D reordering using the index mapping illustrated by the above equations.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The second stage is the butterfly calculation.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Each butterfly calculates eight points together as shown in the figure just below, where $c(\varphi _{i})=\cos(\varphi _{i})$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The whole 3-D DCT calculation needs $~[\log _{2}N]~$ stages, and each stage involves $~{\tfrac {1}{8}}\ N^{3}~$ butterflies.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Each butterfly requires seven real multiplications (including trivial multiplications) and 24 real additions (including trivial additions).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The conventional method to calculate MD-DCT-II is using a Row-Column-Frame (RCF) approach, which is computationally complex and less productive on most recent advanced hardware platforms.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The VR DIF algorithm requires fewer multiplications than the RCF algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The total number of multiplications associated with the 3-D DCT VR algorithm is less than that associated with the RCF approach by more than 40%.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In addition, the RCF approach involves matrix transpose and more indexing and data swapping than the VR DIF algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the 3-D DCT VR algorithm more efficient and better suited for 3-D applications that involve the 3-D DCT-II, such as video compression and other 3-D image processing applications.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The main consideration in choosing a fast algorithm is to avoid computational and structural complexities.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] As the technology of computers and DSPs advances, the execution time of arithmetic operations (multiplications and additions) improves and regular computational structure becomes the most important factor.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Therefore, although the above proposed 3-D VR algorithm does not achieve the theoretical lower bound on the number of multiplications, it has a simpler computational structure as compared to other 3-D DCT algorithms.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] It can be implemented in place using a single butterfly and possesses the properties of the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm in 3-D.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Hence, the 3-D VR presents a good choice for reducing arithmetic operations in the calculation of the 3-D DCT-II, while keeping the simple structure that characterizes butterfly-style Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithms.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The image to the right shows a combination of horizontal and vertical frequencies for an 8 × 8 $(~N_{1}=N_{2}=8~)$ two-dimensional DCT.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Each step from left to right and top to bottom is an increase in frequency by a half-cycle.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, moving right one from the top-left square yields a half-cycle increase in the horizontal frequency.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Another move to the right yields two half-cycles.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A move down yields two half-cycles horizontally and a half-cycle vertically.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The source data (8 × 8) is transformed to a linear combination of these 64 frequency squares.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The MD DCT-IV is an extension of 1-D DCT-IV onto an M-dimensional domain.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] We can compute the MD DCT-IV using the regular row-column method, or we can use the polynomial transform method for fast and efficient computation.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The main idea of this algorithm is to use the polynomial transform to directly convert the multidimensional DCT into a series of 1-D DCTs.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Although the direct application of these formulas would require $~{\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})~$ operations, it is possible to compute the same thing with only $~{\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)~$ complexity by factorizing the computation similarly to the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] One can also compute DCTs via FFTs combined with $~{\mathcal {O}}(N)~$ pre- and post-processing steps.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In general, $~{\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)~$ methods to compute DCTs are known as fast cosine transform (FCT) algorithms.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] The most efficient algorithms, in principle, are usually those that are specialized directly for the DCT, as opposed to using an ordinary FFT plus $~{\mathcal {O}}(N)~$ extra operations (see below for an exception).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] This can even be done automatically (Frigo & Johnson 2005).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Algorithms based on the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm are most common, but any other FFT algorithm is also applicable.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, the Winograd FFT algorithm leads to minimal-multiplication algorithms for the DFT, albeit generally at the cost of more additions, and a similar algorithm was proposed by (Feig & Winograd 1992a) for the DCT.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Because the algorithms for DFTs, DCTs, and similar transforms are all so closely related, any improvement in algorithms for one transform will theoretically lead to immediate gains for the other transforms as well (Duhamel & Vetterli 1990).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] While DCT algorithms that employ an unmodified FFT often have some theoretical overhead compared to the best specialized DCT algorithms, the former also have a distinct advantage: Highly optimized FFT programs are widely available.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, in practice, it is often easier to obtain high performance for general lengths N with FFT-based algorithms.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Specialized DCT algorithms, on the other hand, see widespread use for transforms of small, fixed sizes such as the 8 × 8 DCT-II used in JPEG compression, or the small DCTs (or MDCTs) typically used in audio compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] In fact, even the DCT algorithms using an ordinary FFT are sometimes equivalent to pruning the redundant operations from a larger FFT of real-symmetric data, and they can even be optimal from the perspective of arithmetic counts.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a type-II DCT is equivalent to a DFT of size $~4N~$ with real-even symmetry whose even-indexed elements are zero.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Because the even-indexed elements are zero, this radix-4 step is exactly the same as a split-radix step.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] If the subsequent size $~N~$ real-data FFT is also performed by a real-data split-radix algorithm (as in Sorensen et al.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] (1987)), then the resulting algorithm actually matches what was long the lowest published arithmetic count for the power-of-two DCT-II ( $~2N\log _{2}N-N+2~$ real-arithmetic operations).
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] A recent reduction in the operation count to $~{\tfrac {17}{9}}N\log _{2}N+{\mathcal {O}}(N)$ also uses a real-data FFT.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] So, there is nothing intrinsically bad about computing the DCT via an FFT from an arithmetic perspective – it is sometimes merely a question of whether the corresponding FFT algorithm is optimal.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Consider this 8 × 8 grayscale image of capital letter A.
[src:jpeg-xl/discrete-cosine-transform] Each basis function is multiplied by its coefficient and then this product is added to the final image.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] An **image file format** is a file format for a digital image.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] There are many formats that can be used, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Most formats up until 2022 were for storing 2D images, not 3D ones.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The data stored in an image file format may be compressed or uncompressed.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] If the data is compressed, it may be done so using lossy compression or lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] For graphic design applications, vector formats are often used.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Some image file formats support transparency.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] A 3D image can be represented within a 2D format, as in a stereogram or autostereogram, but this 3D image will not be a true light field, and thereby may cause the vergence–accommodation conflict.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Image files are composed of digital data in one of these formats so that the data can be displayed on a digital (computer) display or printed out using a printer.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] A common method for displaying digital image information has historically been rasterization.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The size of raster image files is positively correlated with the number of pixels in the image and the color depth (bits per pixel).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Images can be compressed in various ways, however.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] A compression algorithm stores either an exact representation or an approximation of the original image in a smaller number of bytes that can be expanded back to its uncompressed form with a corresponding decompression algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Images with the same number of pixels and color depth can have very different compressed file sizes.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Considering exactly the same compression, number of pixels, and color depth for two images, different graphical complexity of the original images may also result in very different file sizes after compression due to the nature of compression algorithms.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] With some compression formats, images that are less complex may result in smaller compressed file sizes.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] This characteristic sometimes results in a smaller file size for some lossless formats than lossy formats.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] For example, graphically simple images (i.e., images with large continuous regions like line art or animation sequences) may be losslessly compressed into a GIF or PNG format and result in a smaller file size than a lossy JPEG format.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] With vector images, the file size increases only with the addition of more vectors.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] There are two types of image file compression algorithms: lossless and lossy.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Lossless compression algorithms reduce file size while preserving a perfect copy of the original uncompressed image.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Lossless compression generally, but not always, results in larger files than lossy compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Lossless compression should be used to avoid accumulating stages of re-compression when editing images.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Lossy compression algorithms preserve a representation of the original uncompressed image that may appear to be a perfect copy, but is not a perfect copy.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Often lossy compression is able to achieve smaller file sizes than lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Most lossy compression algorithms allow for variable compression that trades image quality for file size.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Including proprietary types, there are hundreds of image file types.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The PNG, JPEG, and GIF formats are most often used to display images on the Internet.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Some of these graphic formats are listed and briefly described below, separated into the two main families of graphics: raster and vector.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Raster images are further divided into formats primarily aimed at (web) delivery (i.e., supporting relatively strong compression) versus formats primarily aimed at authoring or interchange (uncompressed or only relatively weak compression).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] In addition to straight image formats, Metafile formats are portable formats that can include both raster and vector information.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Examples are application-independent formats such as WMF and EMF.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The metafile format is an intermediate format.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Most applications open metafiles and then save them in their own native format.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Page description language refers to formats used to describe the layout of a printed page containing text, objects, and images.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group) is a lossy compression method; JPEG-compressed images are usually stored in the JFIF (JPEG File Interchange Format) or the Exif (Exchangeable Image File Format) file format.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The JPEG filename extension is JPG or JPEG.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Nearly every digital camera can save images in the JPEG format, which supports eight-bit grayscale images and 24-bit color images (eight bits each for red, green, and blue).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG applies lossy compression to images, which can result in a significant reduction of the file size.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Applications can determine the degree of compression to apply, and the amount of compression affects the visual quality of the result.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] When not too great, the compression does not noticeably affect or detract from the image's quality, but JPEG files suffer generational degradation when repeatedly edited and saved.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) is in normal use limited to an 8-bit palette, or 256 colors (while 24-bit color depth is technically possible).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] GIF is most suitable for storing graphics with few colors, such as simple diagrams, shapes, logos, and cartoon-style images, as it uses LZW lossless compression, which is more effective when large areas have a single color and less effective for photographic or dithered images.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Due to GIF's simplicity and age, it achieved almost universal software support.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Due to its animation capabilities, it is still widely used to provide image animation effects, despite its low compression ratio compared to modern video formats.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The PNG (Portable Network Graphics) file format was created as a free, open-source alternative to GIF.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The PNG file format supports 8-bit (256 colors) paletted images (with optional transparency for all palette colors) and 24-bit truecolor (16 million colors) or 48-bit truecolor with and without an alpha channel – while GIF supports only 8-bit palettes with a single transparent color.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Compared to JPEG, PNG excels when the image has large, uniformly colored areas.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Even for photographs – where JPEG is often the choice for final distribution since its lossy compression typically yields smaller file sizes – PNG is still well-suited to storing images during the editing process because of its lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] PNG provides a patent-free replacement for GIF (though GIF is itself now patent-free) and can also replace many common uses of TIFF.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Indexed-color, grayscale, and truecolor images are supported, plus an optional alpha channel.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The Adam7 interlacing allows an early preview, even when only a small percentage of the image data has been transmitted—useful in online viewing applications like web browsers.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] PNG can store gamma and chromaticity data, as well as ICC profiles, for accurate color matching on heterogeneous platforms.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Animated formats derived from PNG are MNG and APNG, which is backwards compatible with PNG and supported by most browsers.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard enabling both lossless and lossy storage.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The compression methods used are different from the ones in standard JFIF/JPEG; they improve quality and compression ratios, but also require more computational power to process.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 also adds features that are missing in JPEG.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It is not nearly as common as JPEG but it is used currently in professional movie editing and distribution (some digital cinemas, for example, use JPEG 2000 for individual movie frames).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] WebP is an open image format released in 2010 that uses both lossless and lossy compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It was designed by Google to reduce image file size to speed up web page loading: its principal purpose is to supersede JPEG as the primary format for photographs on the web.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on RIFF.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] In 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The support for animation allowed for converting older animated GIFs to animated WebP.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The WebP container (i.e., RIFF container for WebP) allows feature support over and above the basic use case of WebP (i.e., a file containing a single image encoded as a VP8 key frame).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Most typical raster formats cannot store HDR data (32 bit floating point values per pixel component), which is why some relatively old or complex formats are still predominant here, and worth mentioning separately.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Newer alternatives are showing up, though.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] RGBE is the format for HDR images originating from Radiance and also supported by Adobe Photoshop.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG-HDR is a file format from Dolby Labs similar to RGBE encoding, standardized as JPEG XT Part 2.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG XT Part 7 includes support for encoding floating point HDR images in the base 8-bit JPEG file using enhancement layers encoded with four profiles (A-D); Profile A is based on the RGBE format and Profile B on the XDepth format from Trellis Management.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF) is an image container format that was standardized by MPEG on the basis of the ISO base media file format.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] While HEIF can be used with any image compression format, the HEIF standard specifies the storage of HEVC intra-coded images and HEVC-coded image sequences taking advantage of inter-picture prediction.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] AVIF is an image container, that is used to store AV1 encoded images.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It was created by Alliance for open media (AOMedia) and is completely open source and royalty-free.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It supports encoding images in 8, 10 and 12-bit depth.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] JPEG XL is a royalty-free raster-graphics file format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It supports reversible recompression of existing JPEG files, as well as high-precision HDR (up to 32-bit floating point values per pixel component).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It is designed to be usable for both delivery and authoring use cases.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The TIFF (Tag Image File Format) format is a flexible format usually using either the TIFF or TIF filename extension.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The tag structure was designed to be easily extendible, and many vendors have introduced proprietary special-purpose tags – with the result that no one reader handles every flavor of TIFF file.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] TIFFs can be lossy or lossless, depending on the technique chosen for storing the pixel data.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Some offer relatively good lossless compression for bi-level (black&white) images.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Some digital cameras can save images in TIFF format, using the LZW compression algorithm for lossless storage.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] TIFF image format is not widely supported by web browsers, but it remains widely accepted as a photograph file standard in the printing business.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] TIFF can handle device-specific color spaces, such as the CMYK defined by a particular set of printing press inks.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] OCR (Optical Character Recognition) software packages commonly generate some form of TIFF image (often monochromatic) for scanned text pages.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The BMP file format (Windows bitmap) is a raster-based, device-independent file type designed in the early days of computer graphics.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It handles graphic files within the Microsoft Windows OS.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Typically, BMP files are uncompressed and therefore large and lossless; their advantage is their simple structure and wide acceptance in Windows programs.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Netpbm format is a family including the portable pixmap file format (PPM), the portable graymap file format (PGM), and the portable bitmap file format (PBM).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] These are either pure ASCII files or raw binary files with an ASCII header that provide very basic functionality and serve as a lowest common denominator for converting pixmap, graymap, or bitmap files between different platforms.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Several applications refer to them collectively as PNM (Portable Any Map).
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] As opposed to the raster image formats above (where the data describes the characteristics of each individual pixel), vector image formats contain a geometric description which can be rendered smoothly at any desired display size.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] At some point, all vector graphics must be rasterized in order to be displayed on digital monitors.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Vector images may also be displayed with analog CRT technology such as that used in some electronic test equipment, medical monitors, radar displays, laser shows and early video games.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Plotters are printers that use vector data rather than pixel data to draw graphics.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) is a file format for 2D vector graphics, raster graphics, and text, and is defined by ISO/IEC 8632.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] All graphical elements can be specified in a textual source file that can be compiled into a binary file or one of two text representations.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] CGM provides a means of graphics data interchange for computer representation of 2D graphical information independent from any particular application, system, platform, or device.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It has been adopted to some extent in the areas of technical illustration and professional design, but has largely been superseded by formats such as SVG and DXF.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The Gerber format (aka Extended Gerber, RS-274X) is a 2D bi-level image description format developed by Ucamco.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] It is the de facto standard format for printed circuit board or PCB software.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is an open standard created and developed by the World Wide Web Consortium to address the need (and attempts of several corporations) for a versatile, scriptable and all-purpose vector format for the web and otherwise.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] The SVG format does not have a compression scheme of its own, but due to the textual nature of XML, an SVG graphic can be compressed using a program such as gzip.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] Because of its scripting potential, SVG is a key component in web applications: interactive web pages that look and act like applications.
[src:jpeg-xl/image-file-format] These are formats containing both pixel and vector data, possible other data, e.g. the interactive features of PDF.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The Joint Photographic Experts Group created the standard in 1992, based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT) algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG was largely responsible for the proliferation of digital images and digital photos across the Internet and later social media.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG compression is used in a number of image file formats.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG/Exif is the most common image format used by digital cameras and other photographic image capture devices; along with JPEG/JFIF, it is the most common format for storing and transmitting photographic images on the World Wide Web.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] These format variations are often not distinguished and are simply called JPEG.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The MIME media type for JPEG is "image/jpeg", except in older Internet Explorer versions, which provide a MIME type of "image/pjpeg" when uploading JPEG images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG files usually have a filename extension of "jpg" or "jpeg".
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG/JFIF supports a maximum image size of 65,535×65,535 pixels, hence up to 4 gigapixels for an aspect ratio of 1:1.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In 2000, the JPEG group introduced a format intended to be a successor, JPEG 2000, but it was unable to replace the original JPEG as the dominant image standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The original JPEG specification published in 1992 implements processes from various earlier research papers and patents cited by the CCITT (now ITU-T) and Joint Photographic Experts Group.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The basis for JPEG's lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed as an image compression technique in 1972.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Ahmed published the DCT algorithm with T.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Rao in a 1974 paper, which is cited in the JPEG specification.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG specification cites patents from several companies.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The following patents provided the basis for its arithmetic coding algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG specification also cites three other patents from IBM.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Other companies cited as patent holders include AT&T (two patents) and Canon Inc.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Absent from the list is U.S. patent 4,698,672, filed by Compression Labs' Wen-Hsiung Chen and Daniel J.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The patent describes a DCT-based image compression algorithm, and would later be a cause of controversy in 2002 (see *Patent controversy* below).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] However, the JPEG specification did cite two earlier research papers by Wen-Hsiung Chen, published in 1977 and 1984.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] "JPEG" stands for Joint Photographic Experts Group, the name of the committee that created the JPEG standard and other still picture coding standards.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The "Joint" stood for ISO TC97 WG8 and CCITT SGVIII.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Founded in 1986, the group developed the JPEG standard during the late 1980s.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The group published the JPEG standard in 1992.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In 1987, ISO TC 97 became ISO/IEC JTC 1 and, in 1992, CCITT became ITU-T.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Currently on the JTC1 side, JPEG is one of two sub-groups of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 29, Working Group 1 (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 29/WG 1) – titled as *Coding of still pictures*.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] On the ITU-T side, ITU-T SG16 is the respective body.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The original JPEG Group was organized in 1986, issuing the first JPEG standard in 1992, which was approved in September 1992 as **ITU-T Recommendation T.81** and, in 1994, as **ISO/IEC 10918-1**.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG standard specifies the codec, which defines how an image is compressed into a stream of bytes and decompressed back into an image, but not the file format used to contain that stream.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The Exif and JFIF standards define the commonly used file formats for interchange of JPEG-compressed images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG standards are formally named as *Information technology – Digital compression and coding of continuous-tone still images*.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Ecma International TR/98 specifies the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF); the first edition was published in June 2009.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In 2002, Forgent Networks asserted that it owned and would enforce patent rights on the JPEG technology, arising from a patent that had been filed on 27 October 1986, and granted on 6 October 1987: U.S. patent 4,698,672 by Compression Labs' Wen-Hsiung Chen and Daniel J.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] While Forgent did not own Compression Labs at the time, Chen later sold Compression Labs to Forgent, before Chen went on to work for Cisco.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This led to Forgent acquiring ownership over the patent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Forgent's 2002 announcement created a furor reminiscent of Unisys' attempts to assert its rights over the GIF image compression standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG committee investigated the patent claims in 2002 and were of the opinion that they were invalidated by prior art, a view shared by various experts.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Between 2002 and 2004, Forgent was able to obtain about US$105 million by licensing their patent to some 30 companies.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In April 2004, Forgent sued 31 other companies to enforce further license payments.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In July of the same year, a consortium of 21 large computer companies filed a countersuit, with the goal of invalidating the patent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In addition, Microsoft launched a separate lawsuit against Forgent in April 2005.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In February 2006, the United States Patent and Trademark Office agreed to re-examine Forgent's JPEG patent at the request of the Public Patent Foundation.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] On 26 May 2006, the USPTO found the patent invalid based on prior art.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The USPTO also found that Forgent knew about the prior art, yet it intentionally avoided telling the Patent Office.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This made any appeal to reinstate the patent highly unlikely to succeed.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Forgent also possesses a similar patent granted by the European Patent Office in 1994, though it is unclear how enforceable it is.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] As of 27 October 2006, the U.S. patent's 20-year term appears to have expired, and in November 2006, Forgent agreed to abandon enforcement of patent claims against use of the JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG committee has as one of its explicit goals that their standards (in particular their baseline methods) be implementable without payment of license fees, and they have secured appropriate license rights for their JPEG 2000 standard from over 20 large organizations.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Beginning in August 2007, another company, Global Patent Holdings, LLC claimed that its patent (U.S. patent 5,253,341) issued in 1993, is infringed by the downloading of JPEG images on either a website or through e-mail.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] If not invalidated, this patent could apply to any website that displays JPEG images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The patent was under reexamination by the U.S.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office from 2000 to 2007; in July 2007, the Patent Office revoked all of the original claims of the patent but found that an additional claim proposed by Global Patent Holdings (claim 17) was valid.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Global Patent Holdings then filed a number of lawsuits based on claim 17 of its patent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In its first two lawsuits following the reexamination, both filed in Chicago, Illinois, Global Patent Holdings sued the Green Bay Packers, CDW, Motorola, Apple, Orbitz, OfficeMax, Caterpillar, Kraft and Peapod as defendants.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] A third lawsuit was filed on 5 December 2007, in South Florida against ADT Security Services, AutoNation, Florida Crystals Corp., HearUSA, MovieTickets.com, Ocwen Financial Corp. and Tire Kingdom, and a fourth lawsuit on 8 January 2008, in South Florida against the Boca Raton Resort & Club.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] A fifth lawsuit was filed against Global Patent Holdings in Nevada.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] That lawsuit was filed by Zappos.com, Inc., which was allegedly threatened by Global Patent Holdings, and sought a judicial declaration that the '341 patent is invalid and not infringed.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office to reexamine the sole remaining claim of the '341 patent on the basis of new prior art.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office agreed to reexamine the '341 patent, finding that the new prior art raised substantial new questions regarding the patent's validity.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In light of the reexamination, the accused infringers in four of the five pending lawsuits have filed motions to suspend (stay) their cases until completion of the U.S.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office's review of the '341 patent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] On 23 April 2008, a judge presiding over the two lawsuits in Chicago, Illinois granted the motions in those cases.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] On 22 July 2008, the Patent Office issued the first "Office Action" of the second reexamination, finding the claim invalid based on nineteen separate grounds.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] On 24 November 2009, a Reexamination Certificate was issued cancelling all claims.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Beginning in 2011 and continuing as of early 2013, an entity known as Princeton Digital Image Corporation, based in Eastern Texas, began suing large numbers of companies for alleged infringement of U.S. patent 4,813,056.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Princeton claims that the JPEG image compression standard infringes the '056 patent and has sued large numbers of websites, retailers, camera and device manufacturers and resellers.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The patent was originally owned and assigned to General Electric.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The patent expired in December 2007, but Princeton has sued large numbers of companies for "past infringement" of this patent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] General Electric's involvement in the suit is unknown, although court records indicate that it assigned the patent to Princeton in 2009 and retains certain rights in the patent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG compression algorithm operates at its best on photographs and paintings of realistic scenes with smooth variations of tone and color.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] For web usage, where reducing the amount of data used for an image is important for responsive presentation, JPEG's compression benefits make JPEG popular.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG/Exif is also the most common format saved by digital cameras.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] However, JPEG is not well suited for line drawings and other textual or iconic graphics, where the sharp contrasts between adjacent pixels can cause noticeable artifacts.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Such images are better saved in a lossless graphics format such as TIFF, GIF, PNG, or a raw image format.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The JPEG standard includes a lossless coding mode, but that mode is not supported in most products.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] As the typical use of JPEG is a lossy compression method, which reduces the image fidelity, it is inappropriate for exact reproduction of imaging data (such as some scientific and medical imaging applications and certain technical image processing work).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG is also not well suited to files that will undergo multiple edits, as some image quality is lost each time the image is recompressed, particularly if the image is cropped or shifted, or if encoding parameters are changed – see digital generation loss for details.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] To prevent image information loss during sequential and repetitive editing, the first edit can be saved in a lossless format, subsequently edited in that format, then finally published as JPEG for distribution.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] JPEG uses a lossy form of compression based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This mathematical operation converts each frame/field of the video source from the spatial (2D) domain into the frequency domain (a.k.a. transform domain).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] A perceptual model based loosely on how the human psychovisual system discards high-frequency information, i.e. sharp transitions in intensity, and color hue.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In the transform domain, the process of reducing information is called quantization.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The quantized coefficients are then sequenced and losslessly packed into the output bitstream.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Nearly all software implementations of JPEG permit user control over the compression ratio (as well as other optional parameters), allowing the user to trade off picture-quality for smaller file size.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In embedded applications (such as miniDV, which uses a similar DCT-compression scheme), the parameters are pre-selected and fixed for the application.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The compression method is usually lossy, meaning that some original image information is lost and cannot be restored, possibly affecting image quality.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] There is an optional lossless mode defined in the JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] However, this mode is not widely supported in products.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] There is also an interlaced *progressive* JPEG format, in which data is compressed in multiple passes of progressively higher detail.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This is ideal for large images that will be displayed while downloading over a slow connection, allowing a reasonable preview after receiving only a portion of the data.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] However, support for progressive JPEGs is not universal.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] When progressive JPEGs are received by programs that do not support them (such as versions of Internet Explorer before Windows 7) the software displays the image only after it has been completely downloaded.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] There are also many medical imaging, traffic and camera applications that create and process 12-bit JPEG images both grayscale and color.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] 12-bit JPEG format is included in an Extended part of the JPEG specification.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The libjpeg codec supports 12-bit JPEG and there even exists a high-performance version.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Several alterations to a JPEG image can be performed losslessly (that is, without recompression and the associated quality loss) as long as the image size is a multiple of 1 MCU block (Minimum Coded Unit) (usually 16 pixels in both directions, for 4:2:0 chroma subsampling).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Blocks can be rotated in 90-degree increments, flipped in the horizontal, vertical and diagonal axes and moved about in the image.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Not all blocks from the original image need to be used in the modified one.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The top and left edge of a JPEG image must lie on an 8 × 8 pixel block boundary (or 16 × 16 pixel for larger MCU sizes), but the bottom and right edge need not do so.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This limits the possible **lossless crop** operations, and prevents flips and rotations of an image whose bottom or right edge does not lie on a block boundary for all channels (because the edge would end up on top or left, where – as aforementioned – a block boundary is obligatory).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Rotations where the image is not a multiple of 8 or 16, which value depends upon the chroma subsampling, are not lossless.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Rotating such an image causes the blocks to be recomputed which results in loss of quality.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] When using lossless cropping, if the bottom or right side of the crop region is not on a block boundary, then the rest of the data from the partially used blocks will still be present in the cropped file and can be recovered.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] It is also possible to transform between baseline and progressive formats without any loss of quality, since the only difference is the order in which the coefficients are placed in the file.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Furthermore, several JPEG images can be losslessly joined, as long as they were saved with the same quality and the edges coincide with block boundaries.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The file format known as "JPEG Interchange Format" (JIF) is specified in Annex B of the standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Several additional standards have evolved to address these issues.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The first of these, released in 1992, was the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF), followed in recent years by Exchangeable image file format (Exif) and ICC color profiles.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Both of these formats use the actual JIF byte layout, consisting of different *markers*, but in addition, employ one of the JIF standard's extension points, namely the *application markers*: JFIF uses APP0, while Exif uses APP1.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Within these segments of the file that were left for future use in the JIF standard and are not read by it, these standards add specific metadata.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Thus, in some ways, JFIF is a cut-down version of the JIF standard in that it specifies certain constraints (such as not allowing all the different encoding modes), while in other ways, it is an extension of JIF due to the added metadata.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Image files that employ JPEG compression are commonly called "JPEG files", and are stored in variants of the JIF image format.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Most image capture devices (such as digital cameras) that output JPEG are actually creating files in the Exif format, the format that the camera industry has standardized on for metadata interchange.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] On the other hand, since the Exif standard does not allow color profiles, most image editing software stores JPEG in JFIF format, and includes the APP1 segment from the Exif file to include the metadata in an almost-compliant way; the JFIF standard is interpreted somewhat flexibly.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Strictly speaking, the JFIF and Exif standards are incompatible, because each specifies that its marker segment (APP0 or APP1, respectively) appear first.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] In practice, most JPEG files contain a JFIF marker segment that precedes the Exif header.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This allows older readers to correctly handle the older format JFIF segment, while newer readers also decode the following Exif segment, being less strict about requiring it to appear first.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] The most common filename extensions for files employing JPEG compression are **`.jpg`** and **`.jpeg`**, though `.jpe`, `.jfif` and `.jif` are also used.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] It is also possible for JPEG data to be embedded in other file types – TIFF encoded files often embed a JPEG image as a thumbnail of the main image; and MP3 files can contain a JPEG of cover art in the ID3v2 tag.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Many JPEG files embed an ICC color profile (color space).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Commonly used color profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Because these color spaces use a non-linear transformation, the dynamic range of an 8-bit JPEG file is about 11 stops; see gamma curve.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] If the image doesn't specify color profile information (*untagged*), the color space is assumed to be sRGB for the purposes of display on webpages.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] A JPEG image consists of a sequence of *segments*, each beginning with a *marker*, each of which begins with a 0xFF byte, followed by a byte indicating what kind of marker it is.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Some markers consist of just those two bytes; others are followed by two bytes (high then low), indicating the length of marker-specific payload data that follows.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] (The length includes the two bytes for the length, but not the two bytes for the marker.) Some markers are followed by entropy-coded data; the length of such a marker does not include the entropy-coded data.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Within the entropy-coded data, after any 0xFF byte, a 0x00 byte is inserted by the encoder before the next byte, so that there does not appear to be a marker where none is intended, preventing framing errors.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] This technique, called byte stuffing (see JPEG specification section F.1.2.3), is only applied to the entropy-coded data, not to marker payload data.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] There are other *Start Of Frame* markers that introduce other kinds of JPEG encodings.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Since several vendors might use the same APP*n* marker type, application-specific markers often begin with a standard or vendor name (e.g., "Exif" or "Adobe") or some other identifying string.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] At a restart marker, block-to-block predictor variables are reset, and the bitstream is synchronized to a byte boundary.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Restart markers provide means for recovery after bitstream error, such as transmission over an unreliable network or file corruption.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p01] Since the runs of macroblocks between restart markers may be independently decoded, these runs may be decoded in parallel.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Although a JPEG file can be encoded in various ways, most commonly it is done with JFIF encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The resolution of the chroma data is reduced, usually by a factor of 2 or 3.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This reflects the fact that the eye is less sensitive to fine color details than to fine brightness details.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The image is split into blocks of 8×8 pixels, and for each block, each of the Y, CB, and CR data undergoes the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] A DCT is similar to a Fourier transform in the sense that it produces a kind of spatial frequency spectrum.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The amplitudes of the frequency components are quantized.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Human vision is much more sensitive to small variations in color or brightness over large areas than to the strength of high-frequency brightness variations.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Therefore, the magnitudes of the high-frequency components are stored with a lower accuracy than the low-frequency components.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The quality setting of the encoder (for example 50 or 95 on a scale of 0–100 in the Independent JPEG Group's library) affects to what extent the resolution of each frequency component is reduced.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] If an excessively low quality setting is used, the high-frequency components are discarded altogether.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The resulting data for all 8×8 blocks is further compressed with a lossless algorithm, a variant of Huffman encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The decoding process reverses these steps, except the *quantization* because it is irreversible.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In the remainder of this section, the encoding and decoding processes are described in more detail.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Many of the options in the JPEG standard are not commonly used, and as mentioned above, most image software uses the simpler JFIF format when creating a JPEG file, which among other things specifies the encoding method.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Here is a brief description of one of the more common methods of encoding when applied to an input that has 24 bits per pixel (eight each of red, green, and blue).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This particular option is a lossy data compression method.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] First, the image should be converted from RGB (by default sRGB, but other color spaces are possible) into a different color space called Y′CBCR (or, informally, YCbCr).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It has three components Y', CB and CR: the Y' component represents the brightness of a pixel, and the CB and CR components represent the chrominance (split into blue and red components).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This is basically the same color space as used by digital color television as well as digital video including video DVDs.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The Y′CBCR color space conversion allows greater compression without a significant effect on perceptual image quality (or greater perceptual image quality for the same compression).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The compression is more efficient because the brightness information, which is more important to the eventual perceptual quality of the image, is confined to a single channel.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This more closely corresponds to the perception of color in the human visual system.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The color transformation also improves compression by statistical decorrelation.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] A particular conversion to Y′CBCR is specified in the JFIF standard, and should be performed for the resulting JPEG file to have maximum compatibility.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] However, some JPEG implementations in "highest quality" mode do not apply this step and instead keep the color information in the RGB color model, where the image is stored in separate channels for red, green and blue brightness components.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This results in less efficient compression, and would not likely be used when file size is especially important.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Due to the densities of color- and brightness-sensitive receptors in the human eye, humans can see considerably more fine detail in the brightness of an image (the Y' component) than in the hue and color saturation of an image (the Cb and Cr components).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Using this knowledge, encoders can be designed to compress images more efficiently.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The transformation into the Y′CBCR color model enables the next usual step, which is to reduce the spatial resolution of the Cb and Cr components (called "downsampling" or "chroma subsampling").
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The ratios at which the downsampling is ordinarily done for JPEG images are 4:4:4 (no downsampling), 4:2:2 (reduction by a factor of 2 in the horizontal direction), or (most commonly) 4:2:0 (reduction by a factor of 2 in both the horizontal and vertical directions).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] For the rest of the compression process, Y', Cb and Cr are processed separately and in a very similar manner.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] After subsampling, each channel must be split into 8×8 blocks.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Depending on chroma subsampling, this yields Minimum Coded Unit (MCU) blocks of size 8×8 (4:4:4 – no subsampling), 16×8 (4:2:2), or most commonly 16×16 (4:2:0).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In video compression MCUs are called macroblocks.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] If the data for a channel does not represent an integer number of blocks then the encoder must fill the remaining area of the incomplete blocks with some form of dummy data.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Next, each 8×8 block of each component (Y, Cb, Cr) is converted to a frequency-domain representation, using a normalized, two-dimensional type-II discrete cosine transform (DCT), see Citation 1 in discrete cosine transform.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The DCT is sometimes referred to as "type-II DCT" in the context of a family of transforms as in discrete cosine transform, and the corresponding inverse (IDCT) is denoted as "type-III DCT".
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Before computing the DCT of the 8×8 block, its values are shifted from a positive range to one centered on zero.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] For an 8-bit image, each entry in the original block falls in the range $[0,255]$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The midpoint of the range (in this case, the value 128) is subtracted from each entry to produce a data range that is centered on zero, so that the modified range is $[-128,127]$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This step reduces the dynamic range requirements in the DCT processing stage that follows.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Note the top-left corner entry with the rather large magnitude.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This is the DC coefficient (also called the constant component), which defines the basic hue for the entire block.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The remaining 63 coefficients are the AC coefficients (also called the alternating components).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The advantage of the DCT is its tendency to aggregate most of the signal in one corner of the result, as may be seen above.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The quantization step to follow accentuates this effect while simultaneously reducing the overall size of the DCT coefficients, resulting in a signal that is easy to compress efficiently in the entropy stage.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The DCT temporarily increases the bit-depth of the data, since the DCT coefficients of an 8-bit/component image take up to 11 or more bits (depending on fidelity of the DCT calculation) to store.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This may force the codec to temporarily use 16-bit numbers to hold these coefficients, doubling the size of the image representation at this point; these values are typically reduced back to 8-bit values by the quantization step.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The temporary increase in size at this stage is not a performance concern for most JPEG implementations, since typically only a very small part of the image is stored in full DCT form at any given time during the image encoding or decoding process.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The human eye is good at seeing small differences in brightness over a relatively large area, but not so good at distinguishing the exact strength of a high frequency brightness variation.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This allows one to greatly reduce the amount of information in the high frequency components.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This is done by simply dividing each component in the frequency domain by a constant for that component, and then rounding to the nearest integer.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This rounding operation is the only lossy operation in the whole process (other than chroma subsampling) if the DCT computation is performed with sufficiently high precision.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] As a result of this, it is typically the case that many of the higher frequency components are rounded to zero, and many of the rest become small positive or negative numbers, which take many fewer bits to represent.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The elements in the quantization matrix control the compression ratio, with larger values producing greater compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] where G is the unquantized DCT coefficients; Q is the quantization matrix above; and B is the quantized DCT coefficients.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Notice that most of the higher-frequency elements of the sub-block (i.e., those with an *x* or *y* spatial frequency greater than 4) are quantized into zero values.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Entropy coding is a special form of lossless data compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It involves arranging the image components in a "zigzag" order employing run-length encoding (RLE) algorithm that groups similar frequencies together, inserting length coding zeros, and then using Huffman coding on what is left.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The JPEG standard also allows, but does not require, decoders to support the use of arithmetic coding, which is mathematically superior to Huffman coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] However, this feature has rarely been used, as it was historically covered by patents requiring royalty-bearing licenses, and because it is slower to encode and decode compared to Huffman coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Arithmetic coding typically makes files about 5–7% smaller.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The previous quantized DC coefficient is used to predict the current quantized DC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The difference between the two is encoded rather than the actual value.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The encoding of the 63 quantized AC coefficients does not use such prediction differencing.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The zigzag sequence for the above quantized coefficients are shown below.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] If the *i*-th block is represented by $B_{i}$ and positions within each block are represented by $(p,q)$ where $p=0,1,...,7$ and $q=0,1,...,7$ , then any coefficient in the DCT image can be represented as $B_{i}(p,q)$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This encoding mode is called baseline *sequential* encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Baseline JPEG also supports *progressive* encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] While sequential encoding encodes coefficients of a single block at a time (in a zigzag manner), progressive encoding encodes similar-positioned batch of coefficients of all blocks in one go (called a *scan*), followed by the next batch of coefficients of all blocks, and so on.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Once all similar-positioned coefficients have been encoded, the next position to be encoded is the one occurring next in the zigzag traversal as indicated in the figure above.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In the rest of the article, it is assumed that the coefficient pattern generated is due to sequential mode.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In order to encode the above generated coefficient pattern, JPEG uses Huffman encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The JPEG standard provides general-purpose Huffman tables; encoders may also choose to generate Huffman tables optimized for the actual frequency distributions in images being encoded.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The run-length encoding works by examining each non-zero AC coefficient x and determining how many zeroes came before the previous AC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Both *RUNLENGTH* and *SIZE* rest on the same byte, meaning that each only contains four bits of information.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The higher bits deal with the number of zeroes, while the lower bits denote the number of bits necessary to encode the value of x.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This has the immediate implication of *Symbol 1* being only able store information regarding the first 15 zeroes preceding the non-zero AC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] However, JPEG defines two special Huffman code words.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] One is for ending the sequence prematurely when the remaining coefficients are zero (called "End-of-Block" or "EOB"), and another when the run of zeroes goes beyond 15 before reaching a non-zero AC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In such a case where 16 zeroes are encountered before a given non-zero AC coefficient, *Symbol 1* is encoded "specially" as: (15, 0)(0).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The overall process continues until "EOB" – denoted by (0, 0) – is reached.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] (The first value in the matrix, −26, is the DC coefficient; it is not encoded the same way.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] From here, frequency calculations are made based on occurrences of the coefficients.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In our example block, most of the quantized coefficients are small numbers that are not preceded immediately by a zero coefficient.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] These more-frequent cases will be represented by shorter code words.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The resulting compression ratio can be varied according to need by being more or less aggressive in the divisors used in the quantization phase.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Ten to one compression usually results in an image that cannot be distinguished by eye from the original.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] A compression ratio of 100:1 is usually possible, but will look distinctly artifacted compared to the original.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The appropriate level of compression depends on the use to which the image will be put.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Those who use the World Wide Web may be familiar with the irregularities known as compression artifacts that appear in JPEG images, which may take the form of noise around contrasting edges (especially curves and corners), or "blocky" images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] These are due to the quantization step of the JPEG algorithm.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] They are especially noticeable around sharp corners between contrasting colors (text is a good example, as it contains many such corners).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The analogous artifacts in MPEG video are referred to as *mosquito noise,* as the resulting "edge busyness" and spurious dots, which change over time, resemble mosquitoes swarming around the object.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] These artifacts can be reduced by choosing a lower level of compression; they may be completely avoided by saving an image using a lossless file format, though this will result in a larger file size.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The images created with ray-tracing programs have noticeable blocky shapes on the terrain.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Certain low-intensity compression artifacts might be acceptable when simply viewing the images, but can be emphasized if the image is subsequently processed, usually resulting in unacceptable quality.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Consider the example below, demonstrating the effect of lossy compression on an edge detection processing step.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Some programs allow the user to vary the amount by which individual blocks are compressed.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Stronger compression is applied to areas of the image that show fewer artifacts.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This way it is possible to manually reduce JPEG file size with less loss of quality.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Since the quantization stage *always* results in a loss of information, JPEG standard is always a lossy compression codec.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] (Information is lost both in quantizing and rounding of the floating-point numbers.) Even if the quantization matrix is a matrix of ones, information will still be lost in the rounding step.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Decoding to display the image consists of doing all the above in reverse.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] which closely resembles the original DCT coefficient matrix for the top-left portion.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Slight differences are noticeable between the original (top) and decompressed image (bottom), which is most readily seen in the bottom-left corner.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In general, the decompression process may produce values outside the original input range of $[0,255]$ .
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] If this occurs, the decoder needs to clip the output values so as to keep them within that range to prevent overflow when storing the decompressed image with the original bit depth.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The error is most noticeable in the bottom-left corner where the bottom-left pixel becomes darker than the pixel to its immediate right.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The required implementation precision of a JPEG codec is implicitly defined through the requirements formulated for compliance to the JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] These requirements are specified in ITU.T Recommendation T.83 | ISO/IEC 10918-2.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] For example, the output of a decoder implementation must not exceed an error of one quantization unit in the DCT domain when applied to the reference testing codestreams provided as part of the above standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] While unusual, and unlike many other and more modern standards, ITU.T T.83 | ISO/IEC 10918-2 does not formulate error bounds in the image domain.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPEG compression artifacts blend well into photographs with detailed non-uniform textures, allowing higher compression ratios.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Notice how a higher compression ratio first affects the high-frequency textures in the upper-left corner of the image, and how the contrasting lines become more fuzzy.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The very high compression ratio severely affects the quality of the image, although the overall colors and image form are still recognizable.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] However, the precision of colors suffer less (for a human eye) than the precision of contours (based on luminance).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] For information, the uncompressed 24-bit RGB bitmap image below (73,242 pixels) would require 219,726 bytes (excluding all other information headers).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The filesizes indicated below include the internal JPEG information headers and some metadata.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] For highest quality images (Q=100), about 8.25 bits per color pixel is required.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] On grayscale images, a minimum of 6.5 bits per pixel is enough (a comparable Q=100 quality color information requires about 25% more encoded bits).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The highest quality image below (Q=100) is encoded at nine bits per color pixel, the medium quality image (Q=25) uses one bit per color pixel.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] For most applications, the quality factor should not go below 0.75 bit per pixel (Q=12.5), as demonstrated by the low quality image.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The image at lowest quality uses only 0.13 bit per pixel, and displays very poor color.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This is useful when the image will be displayed in a significantly scaled-down size.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] A method for creating better quantization matrices for a given image quality using PSNR instead of the Q factor is described in Minguillón & Pujol (2001).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The medium quality photo uses only 4.3% of the storage space required for the uncompressed image, but has little noticeable loss of detail or visible artifacts.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] However, once a certain threshold of compression is passed, compressed images show increasingly visible defects.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] See the article on rate–distortion theory for a mathematical explanation of this threshold effect.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] A particular limitation of JPEG in this regard is its non-overlapped 8×8 block transform structure.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] More modern designs such as JPEG 2000 and JPEG XR exhibit a more graceful degradation of quality as the bit usage decreases – by using transforms with a larger spatial extent for the lower frequency coefficients and by using overlapping transform basis functions.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] From 2004 to 2008, new research emerged on ways to further compress the data contained in JPEG images without modifying the represented image.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This has applications in scenarios where the original image is only available in JPEG format, and its size needs to be reduced for archiving or transmission.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Standard general-purpose compression tools cannot significantly compress JPEG files.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Typically, such methods can compress existing JPEG files between 15 and 25 percent, and for JPEGs compressed at low-quality settings, can produce improvements of up to 65%.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Several programs are available for lossless recompression of JPEG files.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The files produced by such programs are not compatible with the JPEG standard and require special software to decode.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPS is a stereoscopic JPEG image used for creating 3D effects from 2D images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It contains two static images, one for the left eye and one for the right eye; encoded as two side-by-side images in a single JPEG file.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPEG Stereoscopic (JPS, extension .jps) is a JPEG-based format for stereoscopic images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It has a range of configurations stored in the JPEG APP3 marker field, but usually contains one image of double width, representing two images of identical size in cross-eyed (i.e. left frame on the right half of the image and vice versa) side-by-side arrangement.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This file format can be viewed as a JPEG without any special software, or can be processed for rendering in other modes.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPEG Multi-Picture Format (MPO, extension .mpo) is a JPEG-based format for storing multiple images in a single file.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It contains two or more JPEG files concatenated together.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It also defines a JPEG APP2 marker segment for image description.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Various devices use it to store 3D images, such as Fujifilm FinePix Real 3D W1, HTC Evo 3D, JVC GY-HMZ1U AVCHD/MVC extension camcorder, Nintendo 3DS, Panasonic Lumix DMC-TZ20, DMC-TZ30, DMC-TZ60, DMC-TS4 (FT4), and Sony DSC-HX7V.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Other devices use it to store "preview images" that can be displayed on a TV.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In the last few years, due to the growing use of stereoscopic images, much effort has been spent by the scientific community to develop algorithms for stereoscopic image compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] A very important implementation of a JPEG codec is the free programming library **libjpeg** of the Independent JPEG Group.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It was first published in 1991 and was key for the success of the standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] This library was used in countless applications.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The development went quiet in 1998; when libjpeg resurfaced with the 2009 version 7, it broke ABI compatibility with previous versions.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Version 8 of 2010 introduced non-standard extensions, a decision criticized by the original IJG leader Tom Lane.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] ISO/IEC Joint Photographic Experts Group maintains the other reference software implementation under the JPEG XT heading.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It can encode both base JPEG (ISO/IEC 10918-1 and 18477–1) and JPEG XT extensions (ISO/IEC 18477 Parts 2 and 6–9), as well as JPEG-LS (ISO/IEC 14495).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In 2016, "JPEG on steroids" was introduced as an option for the ISO JPEG XT reference implementation.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] There is persistent interest in encoding JPEG in unconventional ways that maximize image quality for a given file size.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In 2014, Mozilla created **MozJPEG** from libjpeg-turbo, a slower but higher-quality encoder intended for web images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In March 2017, Google released the open source project Guetzli, which trades off a much longer encoding time for smaller file size (similar to what Zopfli does for PNG and other lossless data formats).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] In April 2024, Google introduced **Jpegli**, a new JPEG coding library that offers enhanced capabilities and a 35% compression ratio improvement at high quality compression settings, while the coding speed is comparable with MozJPEG.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The Joint Photographic Experts Group has developed several newer standards meant to complement or replace the functionality of the original JPEG format.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Originating in 1993 and published as ISO-14495-1/ITU-T.87, JPEG LS offers a low-complexity lossless file format which was more efficient than JPEG's original lossless implementation.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It also features a lossy mode close to lossless.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Its functionality is largely limited to that, and largely shares the same limitations of the original JPEG in other aspects.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPEG 2000 was published as ISO/IEC 15444 in December 2000.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It is based on a discrete wavelet transform (DWT) and was designed to completely replace the original JPEG standard and exceed it in every way.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It allows up to 38 bits per colour channel and 16384 channels, more than any other format, with a multitude of colour spaces, and thus high dynamic range (HDR).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Furthermore, it supports alpha transparency coding, billions-by-billions pixel images, which is also more than any other format, and lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It has significantly improved lossy compression ratio with significantly less visible artefacts at strong compression levels.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPEG XT (ISO/IEC 18477) was published in June 2015; it extends base JPEG format with support for higher integer bit depths (up to 16 bit), high dynamic range imaging and floating-point coding, lossless coding, and alpha channel coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Extensions are backward compatible with the base JPEG/JFIF file format and 8-bit lossy compressed image.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] JPEG XT uses an extensible file format based on JFIF.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Extension layers are used to modify the JPEG 8-bit base layer and restore the high-resolution image.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] Existing software is forward compatible and can read the JPEG XT binary stream, though it would only decode the base 8-bit layer.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] It replaces the JPEG format with a new DCT-based royalty-free format and allows efficient transcoding as a storage option for traditional JPEG images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-p02] The new format is designed to exceed the still image compression performance shown by HEIF HM, Daala and WebP.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The **JPEG XL** **Image Coding System** (**JPEG XL**, sometimes shortened to **JXL**) is an image format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] It was developed by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG), Google and Cloudinary.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] It is a free and open standard defined by ISO/IEC 18181.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The standard consists of four parts that cover the *Core coding system*, *File format*, *Conformance testing*, and *Reference software*, respectively.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] JPEG XL features a lossy compression mode called VarDCT built on block-based transform coding, which is similar to — but significantly improves and expands upon — the compression method of JPEG, and a modular mode that allows different features of the format to be combined in a "modular" way.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Modular mode can be used either for lossless image compression, similar to PNG, or as a means to achieve lossy compression in a different way from VarDCT.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The name refers to the design committee (JPEG), the *X* designates the series of its image coding standards published since 2000 (JPEG XT/XR/XS), and *L* stands for "long-term", highlighting the intent to create a future-proof, long-lived format to succeed JPEG/JFIF.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The main authors of the specification are Jyrki Alakuijala, Jon Sneyers, Zoltan Szabadka, and Luca Versari.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Other collaborators are Sami Boukortt, Alex Deymo, Moritz Firsching, Thomas Fischbacher, Eugene Kliuchnikov, Robert Obryk, Alexander Rhatushnyak, Lode Vandevenne, and Jan Wassenberg.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] JPEG XL was designed to become a universal replacement for all established raster formats for the Web.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] To reach widespread adoption (unlike previous attempts, including several JPEG standards), the designers hope for beneficial network effects by offering the single best option for as many popular use cases as possible.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Following a study about the most popular JPEG quality on the Web, developers paid special attention to the range with negligible or no perceived loss, and the default settings were adjusted accordingly.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Several serious attempts at replacing JPEG that provided poor support for the high end of the quality range have failed.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The JPEG XL call for proposals talks about the requirement of substantially better compression efficiency (60% improvement) comparing to JPEG.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The standard is expected to outperform the still image compression performance shown by HEIC, AVIF, WebP, and JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] In 2015, Jon Sneyers of the company *Cloudinary* published his Free Lossless Image Format (FLIF) on which he based his standardization proposal, called the Free Universal Image Format (FUIF), that begot JXL's "modular mode".
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] In 2017 Google's data compression research team in Zurich published the PIK format, the prototype for the frequency transform coding mode.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] In 2018, the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JTC1 / SC29 / WG1) published a call for proposals for JPEG XL, its next-generation image coding standard.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The proposals were submitted by September 2018.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] From seven proposals, the committee selected two as the starting point for the development of the new format: FUIF and PIK.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] In July 2019 the committee published a draft, mainly based on a combination of the two proposals.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The bitstream was informally frozen on 24 December 2020 with the release of version 0.2 of the libjxl reference software.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The file format and core coding system were formally standardized on 13 October 2021 and 30 March 2022 respectively.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Google's stance on JPEG XL was historically ambiguous, as it contributed to the format but refrained from shipping an implementation of it in its browser.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Support in Chromium and Chrome web browsers was introduced for testing April 1, 2021 and removed on December 9, 2022 – with support removed in version 110.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The Chrome team cited a lack of interest from the ecosystem, insufficient improvements, and a wish to focus on improving existing formats as reasons for removing JPEG XL support.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The decision was met with opposition from the community, with many voicing support for JPEG XL on Chromium's bug tracker.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Mozilla expressed security concerns, as they feel that the rather bulky reference decoder would add a substantial amount of attack surface to Firefox.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] They expressed willingness to ship a decoder that meets their criteria if someone provides and integrates a suitable implementation.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The JPEG XL team at Google Research has offered to write a decoder using the Rust programming language but Mozilla maintains neutral position on supporting JPEG XL.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] On November 22, 2022 Pale Moon became the first web browser to release support for JPEG XL to the public with the release of version 31.4.0.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] An extension to enable JPEG XL support in Chrome and Firefox became available in January 2024.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Apple Inc. included native JPEG XL file support starting with iOS/iPadOS 17, macOS 14 Sonoma, and Safari 17. iPhone 16 Pro supports JPEG XL compression when capturing ProRAW photos.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Microsoft added support for opening and saving JPEG XL files for Windows 11 24H2 via the JPEG XL image extension in Microsoft Store.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Also Microsoft Photos added native JPEG XL support in the 2025.11030.20006.0 build.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The raw image format Digital Negative (DNG) allows image data contained within to be compressed using JPEG XL.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Starting in version 1.7.0.0 from June 2023, JPEG XL compression was included as part of the specification.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] This created a basis for later use as part of "Expert RAW" in Samsung Galaxy smartphones and Apple's "ProRAW".
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The PDF Association has stated in the PDF Days Europe 2025 event in September 2025 that they selected JPEG XL as the preferred image format for HDR images embedded for PDF, although no timeline has been given.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] In November 2025 following the decision of the PDF Association, the Chrome team reverted their stance on JPEG XL and announced that it was open to contributions to integrate a memory safe and performant decoder in Blink.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The team would require the decoder implementation to have commitment to long-term maintenance to ship it in Chrome.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] In January 2026, JPEG XL decoding support was merged into Chromium.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Mozilla took a similar stance and after months of work switched from the C++ reference decoder to the same memory safe and performant decoder in January 2026.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] May 2026 saw Mozilla deciding to also integrate JPEG XL support into the Firefox release channel starting with Firefox 152, which was released on June 16th 2026.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Both Chrome and Firefox keep JPEG XL support disabled for now requiring an experimental flag to be set by the user.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] JPEG XL has features aimed at web delivery such as advanced progressive decoding, embedded previews, and minimal header overhead, as well as features aimed at image editing and digital printing, such as multiple layers, CMYK, and spot colors.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] JPEG XL is based on ideas from Google's PIK format and Cloudinary's FUIF format (which was in turn based on FLIF).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Any additional/extra channels (e.g. alpha, depth, thermal, spot colors, etc.) are always encoded in the modular mode.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] It was based on FUIF, combined with elements of lossless PIK, lossless WebP, and new ideas that have been developed during the collaborative phase of the standardization process.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Modular mode allows lossy compression with the help of the modified Haar transform called "squeeze" which has progressive properties, quality of the image increases with the amount of data loaded.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] One of the ways VarDCT-based images can be loaded more progressively is by saving the DC coefficients in a separate "DC frame" that uses modular squeeze: allowing previews corresponding to 1:16, 1:32 etc. subsampled images.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] A squeeze transform can also be used to encode the alpha channel progressively together with VarDCT-encoded color channels, making both modes work in tandem.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] JPEG XL defaults to a visually near-lossless setting that still provides good compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] JPEG XL codec can losslessly transcode a widely supported subset of JPEG files, by directly copying JPEG's DCT block coefficients to 8×8 VarDCT blocks, making smaller file sizes possible due to JPEG XL's superior entropy coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] This process is reversible and it allows for the original JPEG file to be reconstructed bit-for-bit, although constraints limit support for some files.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Prediction is run using a pixel-by-pixel decorrelator without side information, including a parameterized self-correcting weighted ensemble of predictors.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Context modeling includes specialized static models and powerful meta-adaptive models that take local error into account, with a signaled tree structure and predictor selection per context.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Entropy coding is LZ77-enabled and can use either asymmetric numeral systems or prefix codes (useful for low-complexity encoders, or reducing the overhead of short streams).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The reference implementation software is called libjxl.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] It is written in C++ and published on GitHub as free software under the terms of the New BSD License (before 2021 the Apache License 2.0).
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] It supports Unix-like operating systems, like Linux and Apple's OS family, as well as Windows systems.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] It is available from the standard software repositories of all major Linux and BSD distributions.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] An official Rust decoder written by the libjxl team has been created called jxl-rs.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] This has been added to Google Chrome v145 but disabled by default.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Firefox 152 also shipped jxl-rs on stable behind a runtime support flag.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] Since April 2023, the libjxl repository includes Jpegli, an improved JPEG codec that backports applicable new techniques of JPEG XL to the old format, offering image quality improvements even for the decoder.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] A separate repository is also created by Google after the announcement of Jpegli in April 2024.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] As of 2026, web browsers that support JPEG XL had 14% market share.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] The main competitor for JPEG XL is AVIF, which is based on the AV1 video codec in a HEIF container.
[src:jpeg-xl/jpeg-xl] However, it is unclear to what extent this results from inherent properties of the two image formats themselves, and to what extent this results from the engineering focus of the available encoders.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] By operation of the pigeonhole principle, no lossless compression algorithm can shrink the size of all possible data: Some data will get longer by at least one symbol or bit.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Compression algorithms are usually effective for human- and machine-readable documents and cannot shrink the size of random data that contain no redundancy.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression is used in many applications.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For example, it is used in the ZIP file format and in the GNU tool gzip.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] It is also often used as a component within lossy data compression technologies (e.g. lossless mid/side joint stereo preprocessing by MP3 encoders and other lossy audio encoders).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless compression is used in cases where it is important that the original and the decompressed data be identical, or where deviations from the original data would be unfavourable.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Common examples are executable programs, text documents, and source code.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Some image file formats, like PNG or GIF, use only lossless compression, while others like TIFF and MNG may use either lossless or lossy methods.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless audio formats are most often used for archiving or production purposes, while smaller lossy audio files are typically used on portable players and in other cases where storage space is limited or exact replication of the audio is unnecessary.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The primary encoding algorithms used to produce bit sequences are Huffman coding (also used by the deflate algorithm) and arithmetic coding.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Arithmetic coding achieves compression rates close to the best possible for a particular statistical model, which is given by the information entropy, whereas Huffman compression is simpler and faster but produces poor results for models that deal with symbol probabilities close to 1.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] There are two primary ways of constructing statistical models: in a *static* model, the data is analyzed and a model is constructed, then this model is stored with the compressed data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This approach is simple and modular, but has the disadvantage that the model itself can be expensive to store, and also that it forces using a single model for all data being compressed, and so performs poorly on files that contain heterogeneous data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] *Adaptive* models dynamically update the model as the data is compressed.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Both the encoder and decoder begin with a trivial model, yielding poor compression of initial data, but as they learn more about the data, performance improves.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Most popular types of compression used in practice now use adaptive coders.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless compression methods may be categorized according to the type of data they are designed to compress.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] While, in principle, any general-purpose lossless compression algorithm (*general-purpose* meaning that they can accept any bitstring) can be used on any type of data, many are unable to achieve significant compression on data that are not of the form for which they were designed to compress.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Many of the lossless compression techniques used for text also work reasonably well for indexed-color images.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] These techniques take advantage of the specific characteristics of images such as the common phenomenon of contiguous 2-D areas of similar tones.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Every pixel but the first is replaced by the difference to its left neighbor.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This leads to small values having a much higher probability than large values.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This is often also applied to sound files, and can compress files that contain mostly low frequencies and low volumes.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For images, this step can be repeated by taking the difference to the top pixel, and then in videos, the difference to the pixel in the next frame can be taken.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The adaptive encoding uses the probabilities from the previous sample in sound encoding, from the left and upper pixel in image encoding, and additionally from the previous frame in video encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] In the wavelet transformation, the probabilities are also passed through the hierarchy.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Many of these methods are implemented in open-source and proprietary tools, particularly LZW and its variants.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Some algorithms are patented in the United States and other countries and their legal usage requires licensing by the patent holder.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] However, the patents on LZW expired on June 20, 2003.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] As mentioned previously, lossless sound compression is a somewhat specialized area.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless sound compression algorithms can take advantage of the repeating patterns shown by the wave-like nature of the data‍—‍essentially using autoregressive models to predict the "next" value and encoding the (possibly small) difference between the expected value and the actual data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] If the difference between the predicted and the actual data (called the *error*) tends to be small, then certain difference values (like 0, +1, −1 etc. on sample values) become very frequent, which can be exploited by encoding them in few output bits.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] It is sometimes beneficial to compress only the differences between two versions of a file (or, in video compression, of successive images within a sequence).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This is called delta encoding (from the Greek letter Δ, which in mathematics, denotes a difference), but the term is typically only used if both versions are meaningful outside compression and decompression.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For example, while the process of compressing the error in the above-mentioned lossless audio compression scheme could be described as delta encoding from the approximated sound wave to the original sound wave, the approximated version of the sound wave is not meaningful in any other context.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] No lossless compression algorithm can efficiently compress all possible data .
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For this reason, many different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Some of the most common lossless compression algorithms are listed below.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Cryptosystems often compress data (the "plaintext") *before* encryption for added security.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] When properly implemented, compression greatly increases the unicity distance by removing patterns that might facilitate cryptanalysis.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] However, many ordinary lossless compression algorithms produce headers, wrappers, tables, or other predictable output that might instead make cryptanalysis easier.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Thus, cryptosystems must utilize compression algorithms whose output does not contain these predictable patterns.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Genetics compression algorithms (not to be confused with genetic algorithms) are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and specific algorithms adapted to genetic data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published the first genetic compression algorithm that does not rely on external genetic databases for compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression much faster than leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Genomic sequence compression algorithms, also known as DNA sequence compressors, explore the fact that DNA sequences have characteristic properties, such as inverted repeats.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The most successful compressors are XM and GeCo.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For eukaryotes XM is slightly better in compression ratio, though for sequences larger than 100 MB its computational requirements are impractical.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Self-extracting executables contain a compressed application and a decompressor.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] When executed, the decompressor transparently decompresses and runs the original application.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This is especially often used in demo coding, where competitions are held for demos with strict size limits, as small as 1 kilobyte.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This type of compression is not strictly limited to binary executables, but can also be applied to scripts, such as JavaScript.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless compression algorithms and their implementations are routinely tested in head-to-head benchmarks.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] There are a number of better-known compression benchmarks.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Some benchmarks cover only the data compression ratio, so winners in these benchmarks may be unsuitable for everyday use due to the slow speed of the top performers.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Another drawback of some benchmarks is that their data files are known, so some program writers may optimize their programs for best performance on a particular data set.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The winners on these benchmarks often come from the class of context-mixing compression software.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The Compression Ratings website published a chart summary of the "frontier" in compression ratio and time.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The **Silesia corpus** is a collection of files that was created in 2003 as an alternative for the Canterbury corpus and Calgary corpus, based on concerns about how well these represented modern files.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] It contains various data types, including large text documents, executable files, and databases.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] It is widely used in data compression research.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The corpus consists of 12 files, totaling 211MB.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The files were chosen to represent what the author considered to be data types likely to grow rapidly in size over time, such as computer programs and databases, along with more traditional compression benchmarks, such as large text files.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Because it has a broader and more modern selection of datatypes, it is considered a better source of test data for compression algorithms when compared to the Calgary corpus.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms cannot guarantee compression for all input data sets.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] In other words, for any lossless data compression algorithm, there will be an input data set that does not get smaller when processed by the algorithm, and for any lossless data compression algorithm that makes at least one file smaller, there will be at least one file that it makes larger.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Most practical compression algorithms provide an "escape" facility that can turn off the normal coding for files that would become longer by being encoded.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] In theory, only a single additional bit is required to tell the decoder that the normal coding has been turned off for the entire input; however, most encoding algorithms use at least one full byte (and typically more than one) for this purpose.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For example, deflate compressed files never need to grow by more than 5 bytes per 65,535 bytes of input.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] In fact, if we consider files of length N, if all files were equally probable, then for any lossless compression that reduces the size of some file, the expected length of a compressed file (averaged over all possible files of length N) must necessarily be *greater* than N.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] So if we know nothing about the properties of the data we are compressing, we might as well not compress it at all.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] A lossless compression algorithm is useful only when we are more likely to compress certain types of files than others; then the algorithm could be designed to compress those types of data better.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Thus, the main lesson from the argument is not that one risks big losses, but merely that one cannot always win.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] To choose an algorithm always means implicitly to select a *subset* of all files that will become usefully shorter.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] This is the theoretical reason why we need to have different compression algorithms for different kinds of files: there cannot be any algorithm that is good for all kinds of data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Algorithms are generally quite specifically tuned to a particular type of file: for example, lossless audio compression programs do not work well on text files, and vice versa.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] In particular, files of random data cannot be consistently compressed by any conceivable lossless data compression algorithm; indeed, this result is used to *define* the concept of randomness in Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] It is provably impossible to create an algorithm that can losslessly compress any data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Such an algorithm contradicts fundamental laws of mathematics because, if it existed, it could be applied repeatedly to losslessly reduce any file to length 1.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] On the other hand, it has also been proven that there is no algorithm to determine whether a file is incompressible in the sense of Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Hence it is possible that any particular file, even if it appears random, may be significantly compressed, even including the size of the decompressor.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] An example is the digits of the mathematical constant *pi*, which appear random but can be generated by a very small program.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] However, even though it cannot be determined whether a particular file is incompressible, a simple theorem about incompressible strings shows that over 99% of files of any given length cannot be compressed by more than one byte (including the size of the decompressor).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Abstractly, a compression algorithm can be viewed as a function on sequences (normally of octets).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Compression is successful if the resulting sequence is shorter than the original sequence (and the instructions for the decompression map).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For a compression algorithm to be lossless, the compression map must form an injection from "plain" to "compressed" bit sequences.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] The pigeonhole principle prohibits a bijection between the collection of sequences of length *N* and any subset of the collection of sequences of length *N*−1.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Therefore, it is not possible to produce a lossless algorithm that reduces the size of every possible input sequence.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Real compression algorithm designers accept that streams of high information entropy cannot be compressed, and accordingly, include facilities for detecting and handling this condition.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] An obvious way of detection is applying a raw compression algorithm and testing if its output is smaller than its input.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] Sometimes, detection is made by heuristics; for example, a compression application may consider files whose names end in ".zip", ".arj" or ".lha" uncompressible without any more sophisticated detection.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] A common way of handling this situation is quoting input, or uncompressible parts of the input in the output, minimizing the compression overhead.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossless-compression] For example, the zip data format specifies the 'compression method' of 'Stored' for input files that have been copied into the archive verbatim.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] In information technology, **lossy compression**, or **irreversible compression**, is the class of data compression methods that uses inexact approximations and partial data discarding to represent the content.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] These techniques are used to reduce data size for storing, handling, and transmitting content.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Higher degrees of approximation create coarser images as more details are removed.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This is opposed to lossless data compression (reversible data compression) which does not degrade the data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The amount of data reduction possible using lossy compression is much higher than using lossless techniques.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Well-designed lossy compression technology often reduces file sizes significantly before degradation is noticed by the end-user.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Even when noticeable by the user, further data reduction may be desirable (e.g., for real-time communication or to reduce transmission times or storage needs).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The most widely used lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Lossy compression is most commonly used to compress multimedia data (audio, video, and images), especially in applications such as streaming media and internet telephony.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] By contrast, lossless compression is typically required for text and data files, such as bank records and text articles.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] It can be advantageous to make a master lossless file which can then be used to produce additional copies from.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This allows one to avoid basing new compressed copies on a lossy source file, which would yield additional artifacts and further unnecessary information loss.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] It is possible to compress many types of digital data in a way that reduces the size of a computer file needed to store it, or the bandwidth needed to transmit it, with no loss of the full information contained in the original file.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] A picture, for example, is converted to a digital file by considering it to be an array of dots and specifying the color and brightness of each dot.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The original data contains a certain amount of information, and there is a lower bound to the size of a file that can still carry all the information.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Basic information theory says that there is an absolute limit in reducing the size of this data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] When data is compressed, its entropy increases, and it cannot increase indefinitely.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] For example, a compressed ZIP file is smaller than its original, but repeatedly compressing the same file will not reduce the size to nothing.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Most compression algorithms can recognize when further compression would be pointless and would in fact increase the size of the data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] In many cases, files or data streams contain more information than is needed.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] For example, a picture may have more detail than the eye can distinguish when reproduced at the largest size intended; likewise, an audio file does not need a lot of fine detail during a very loud passage.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Developing lossy compression techniques as closely matched to human perception as possible is a complex task.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Sometimes the ideal is a file that provides exactly the same perception as the original, with as much digital information as possible removed; other times, perceptible loss of quality is considered a valid tradeoff.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The terms "irreversible" and "reversible" are preferred over "lossy" and "lossless" respectively for some applications, such as medical image compression, to circumvent the negative implications of "loss".
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The type and amount of loss can affect the utility of the images.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Artifacts or undesirable effects of compression may be clearly discernible yet the result still useful for the intended purpose.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Or lossy compressed images may be 'visually lossless', or in the case of medical images, so-called diagnostically acceptable irreversible compression (DAIC) may have been applied.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Some forms of lossy compression can be thought of as an application of transform coding, which is a type of data compression used for digital images, digital audio signals, and digital video.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The transformation is typically used to enable better (more targeted) quantization.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Knowledge of the application is used to choose information to discard, thereby lowering its bandwidth.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The remaining information can then be compressed via a variety of methods.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] When the output is decoded, the result may not be identical to the original input, but is expected to be close enough for the purpose of the application.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The most common form of lossy compression is a transform coding method, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] DCT is the most widely used form of lossy compression, for popular image compression formats (such as JPEG), video coding standards (such as MPEG and H.264/AVC) and audio compression formats (such as MP3 and AAC).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] In the case of audio data, a popular form of transform coding is perceptual coding, which transforms the raw data to a domain that more accurately reflects the information content.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] For example, rather than expressing a sound file as the amplitude levels over time, one may express it as the frequency spectrum over time, which corresponds more accurately to human audio perception.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This is because uncompressed audio can only reduce file size by lowering bit rate or depth, whereas compressing audio can reduce size while maintaining bit rate and depth.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This compression becomes a selective loss of the least significant data, rather than losing data across the board.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Further, a transform coding may provide a better domain for manipulating or otherwise editing the data – for example, equalization of audio is most naturally expressed in the frequency domain (boost the bass, for instance) rather than in the raw time domain.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] From this point of view, perceptual encoding is not essentially about *discarding* data, but rather about a *better representation* of data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Another use is for backward compatibility and graceful degradation: in color television, encoding color via a luminance-chrominance transform domain (such as YUV) means that black-and-white sets display the luminance, while ignoring the color information.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Lossy compression formats suffer from generation loss: repeatedly compressing and decompressing the file will cause it to progressively lose quality.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This is in contrast with lossless data compression, where data will not be lost via the use of such a procedure.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Information-theoretical foundations for lossy data compression are provided by rate-distortion theory.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Much like the use of probability in optimal coding theory, rate-distortion theory heavily draws on Bayesian estimation and decision theory in order to model perceptual distortion and even aesthetic judgment.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] In some systems the two techniques are combined, with transform codecs being used to compress the error signals generated by the predictive stage.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The advantage of lossy methods over lossless methods is that in some cases a lossy method can produce a much smaller compressed file than any lossless method, while still meeting the requirements of the application.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Lossy methods are most often used for compressing sound, images or videos.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This is because these types of data are intended for human interpretation where the mind can easily "fill in the blanks" or see past very minor errors or inconsistencies – ideally lossy compression is transparent (imperceptible), which can be verified via an ABX test.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Data files using lossy compression are smaller in size and thus cost less to store and to transmit over the Internet, a crucial consideration for streaming video services such as Netflix and streaming audio services such as Spotify.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] When a user acquires a lossily compressed file, (for example, to reduce download time) the retrieved file can be quite different from the original at the bit level while being indistinguishable to the human ear or eye for most practical purposes.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Many compression methods focus on the idiosyncrasies of human physiology, taking into account, for instance, that the human eye can see only certain wavelengths of light.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The psychoacoustic model describes how sound can be highly compressed without degrading perceived quality.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Flaws caused by lossy compression that are noticeable to the human eye or ear are known as compression artifacts.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The compression ratio (that is, the size of the compressed file compared to that of the uncompressed file) of lossy video codecs is nearly always far superior to that of the audio and still-image equivalents.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] An important caveat about lossy compression (formally transcoding), is that editing lossily compressed files causes digital generation loss from the re-encoding.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] This can be avoided by only producing lossy files from (lossless) originals and only editing (copies of) original files, such as images in raw image format instead of JPEG.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] If data which has been compressed lossily is decoded and compressed losslessly, the size of the result can be comparable with the size of the data before lossy compression, but the data already lost cannot be recovered.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] When deciding to use lossy conversion without keeping the original, format conversion may be needed in the future to achieve compatibility with software or devices (format shifting), or to avoid paying patent royalties for decoding or distribution of compressed files.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] By modifying the compressed data directly without decoding and re-encoding, some editing of lossily compressed files without degradation of quality is possible.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Editing which reduces the file size as if it had been compressed to a greater degree, but without more loss than this, is sometimes also possible.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The primary programs for lossless editing of JPEGs are `jpegtran`, and the derived `exiftran` (which also preserves Exif information), and Jpegcrop (which provides a Windows interface).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] These allow the image to be cropped, rotated, flipped, and flopped, or even converted to grayscale (by dropping the chrominance channel).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] While unwanted information is destroyed, the quality of the remaining portion is unchanged.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Some other transforms are possible to some extent, such as joining images with the same encoding (composing side by side, as on a grid) or pasting images such as logos onto existing images (both via Jpegjoin), or scaling.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] The freeware Windows-only IrfanView has some lossless JPEG operations in its `JPG_TRANSFORM` plugin.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Metadata, such as ID3 tags, Vorbis comments, or Exif information, can usually be modified or removed without modifying the underlying data.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Some well-known designs that have this capability include JPEG 2000 for still images and H.264/MPEG-4 AVC based Scalable Video Coding for video.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Such schemes have also been standardized for older designs as well, such as JPEG images with progressive encoding, and MPEG-2 and MPEG-4 Part 2 video, although those prior schemes had limited success in terms of adoption into real-world common usage.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Similar techniques are used in mipmaps, pyramid representations, and more sophisticated scale space methods.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Some audio formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction which when combined reproduce the original signal; the correction can be stripped, leaving a smaller, lossily compressed, file.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, OptimFROG DualStream, and DTS-HD Master Audio in lossless (XLL) mode).
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Researchers have performed lossy compression on text by either using a thesaurus to substitute short words for long ones, or generative text techniques, although these sometimes fall into the related category of lossy data conversion.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] A general kind of lossy compression is to lower the resolution of an image, as in image scaling, particularly decimation.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] One may also remove less "lower information" parts of an image, such as by seam carving.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Many media transforms, such as Gaussian blur, are, like lossy compression, irreversible: the original signal cannot be reconstructed from the transformed signal.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] However, in general these will have the same size as the original, and are not a form of compression.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Lowering resolution has practical uses, as the NASA New Horizons craft transmitted thumbnails of its encounter with Pluto-Charon before it sent the higher resolution images.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Another solution for slow connections is the usage of Image interlacing which progressively defines the image.
[src:jpeg-xl/lossy-compression] Thus a partial transmission is enough to preview the final image, in a lower resolution version, without creating a scaled and a full version too.
